text: some developers kind of equate css with
design
and don't really think of it as
engineering which i think
is very inaccurate css is one of those
languages that is very easy to pick up
quickly and learn things like how to
change a text color but it is very
tricky to master
and that's where we see a lot of the
frustration now because i think what's
happening is
when you look at job listings you will
see like
requires five years of react experience
in javascript
you're not going to see as often you
know requires
semantic html and css styling experience
so boot camps aren't teaching
proper css and html semantics they're
just kind of
focusing on what the resumes need to say
to get a job
and so now we have all of these senior
developers
who have been working in the industry
for years
who don't have a strong baseline for how
to style things on the web and it's
because it's not as valued
in resumes and then you know you find
these companies like kind of struggling
with accessibility and with just getting
things
to have decent user experiences and i
feel like the web
is worse off for it
